Elon Musk forced to leave the post of head of the board of directors of Tesla
The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission and Tesla founder Elon Musk have settled their dispute over the fraud.
This is reported by CNBC News.
According to the channel, within the framework of the agreements reached, Musk will have to leave the post of head of the board of directors of Tesla.
At the same time, the commission allowed Musk to retain the post of head of Tesla.
The founder of Tesla will also have to pay an administrative fine of $20 million.
A similar amount will be recovered from Tesla.
The money will be distributed among the affected investors.
The company must also appoint two independent directors.
Elon Musk is an American entrepreneur on the list of the 50 richest people in the world according to Forbes magazine.
He is the head of the SpaceX Corporation, the neurotechnical company Neuralink and the developer of Tesla electric cars, as well as the co-founder of Paypal.
The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission has previously sued Tesla CEO Elon Musk because of his message on Twitter about the company's possible redemption.
Last month, Musk announced plans to make Tesla a private company and buy back all stocks on the stock exchange at a fixed price of $420.
The stock price of $420 was set allegedly "due to the importance of this number in the culture of marijuana," Bloomberg reported earlier, citing the co-director of the security department of the commission Stephen Peikin.
At the same time, Elon Musk subsequently abandoned his plans to buy back shares.
Commenting on the lawsuit filed against him by the US Securities and Exchange Commission, the businessman said that he considers the allegations of fraud unfounded, and added that he was very disappointed and saddened by these claims.
"Holiness is the most important value of my life, and the facts will prove that I have not in any way violated it," the businessman said in an interview with CNBC.
At the same time, in August, a group of Tesla shareholders filed a collective lawsuit against Musk, complaining of financial losses.
The plaintiffs claimed that the businessman's posts had brought them losses.
In particular, one of the shareholders said that the businessman's tweets were misleading, because of which the sellers of Tesla shares were forced to buy securities at artificially inflated prices to cover their positions.
Other plaintiffs also noted that the careless statements of Elon Musk led to sharp fluctuations in the course.
In September, Elon Musk was accused of exchange machinations by the head of the research company Citron Research.
Meanwhile, if Musk had not been able to settle his dispute with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, he would be threatened with suspension from the company's management and even a prison.
This, in particular, was stated to the CNBC TV channel by the former chairman of the commission Harvey Pitt.
Musk is "a good guy who can't run a car company."
