In Indonesia, after the earthquake, more than 100 prisoners escaped from prison
More than 100 inmates escaped from prison in Central Sulawesi's Indonesian province.
Escape was possible after two powerful earthquakes on the island with a magnitude of 7.2 and 7.4.
According to the newspaper The Jakarta Post, the incident occurred on September 28, when prisoners in the prison of the city of Palu demanded to release them in connection with the tremors.
More than 340 prisoners rioted and set fire to the institution.
The police who arrived at the scene of the emergency partially took the situation under control, but more than 100 people escaped from prison.
The building itself was seriously damaged and the guards had difficulty holding the prisoners.
The number of victims of the earthquake and tsunami that occurred on the island of Sulawesi has risen to 832 people.
In this regard, it is still not possible to establish transport links, electricity and communications with some areas of the island.
