Kosachev: At the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly, the topic of Russia in a negative way was practically absent
The head of the Federation Council Committee on International Affairs Konstantin Kosachev considers the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly successful for Russia and does not exclude that it will be able to become a turning point in the perception of the Russian Federation as an integral participant in the solution of global problems.
"The uniqueness of the current 73rd session, in my opinion, is that the rhetoric to which we have almost become accustomed to in recent years in relation to Russia has now been more muted," the senator said in an interview published Sunday by the Russian Newspaper.
He explained that in previous years, the Russian Federation was sometimes "designated as one of the three main threats to humanity, along with Ebola, then along with climate change or terrorism, Russia was in this row, in any case, in the presentation of a group of Western countries, which expressed quite unanimously in this regard."
At the 73rd session, Kosachev stressed, "Russia's topic in a negative way was practically absent."
"If you carefully analyze the speech of the President of the United States, the President of France, the speech of the Minister of foreign Affairs of Germany, I do not take Ukraine, Georgia, or the British, in any case, the choir was not exactly," - said the politician, noting that Russia "no longer a wall, which is being trained by a tennis ball."
The head of the relevant committee of the Federation Council does not rule out that this indicates a certain trend, which, in his opinion, "will allocate the current session [the UN General Assembly], although this trend may manifest in a year, in two, three."
"I do not rule out that the current session in a sense can be pivotal," - admitted Kosachev, explaining that "too many examples of how Russia manages to move forward in international affairs."
As an example, he cited the situation in Syria, around Iran and North Korea.
"Unfortunately, this is not Ukraine, but I have no doubt that the Russian vision of the Ukrainian crisis will also be in demand over time," the parliamentarian added.
This is due to the fact that "adequate, sound perception of Russia as not just possible - an integral participant in solving the global problems of modernity" appears.
"I don't want to be wrong, but I have a feeling that we're somewhere passing a point beyond which the movement will no longer be a backbone movement, it will be moving forward," he added.
In this context, Kosachev called "a request for a Russian vision of how the modern world should develop another "interesting and important feeling."
"I attended a very many meetings of the head of the Russian delegation [at the session of the General Assembly] of Foreign Minister Sergey Lavrov, I held my own meetings, and I was very pleased to see that if the Russian opinion, the Russian view, by the Russian vision of what is happening in the world, by and large, no one was interested, now the situation is different," - said the Chairman of the Committee of the Federation.
"The so-called new liberal order, which is personified with the West, has no answers to the questions of how to solve world problems due to the obvious shortage of ideas in the global space, a shortage of ideas on how to solve the problems of the Middle East, the problems of terrorism, the problems of nuclear weapons, the problems of nuclear weapons, migration problems."
"And here the request for the Russian vision is becoming more and more obvious," Kosachev expressed confidence, stressing that he considers in this sense "the current session successful for the work of the Russian delegation, successful for Russia."
