AfD became the second most popular in Germany
The anti-immigrant "Alternative for Germany" beats another record of popularity, and Angela Merkel's ratings are falling.
Apparently, the Germans began to seriously get tired of the immigration policy of Angela Merkel, thanks to which the country became a desirable target for millions of refugees from the Middle East.
Most clearly, this is evidenced by the latest polls, according to which the anti-immigrant party "Alternative for Germany" is becoming more popular, and the positions of the ruling block of Merkel and Seehofer are weakening.
This week, the AfD broke another record, rising to the second line in the ranking of popular sympathies.
The right-wing conservatives, with 17 percent of their popularity, managed to bypass the Social Democrats, who had about 16 percent.
The gap of one percentage point can be attributed to statistical error, but it is impossible to note the fact that the AfD from a small group of economists-Evskeptics managed to turn into a serious political force.
Leadership in the overall standings continues to be held by the ruling CSU/CDU bloc, which has about 30 percent.
However, there is a tendency to lose points - in April, the support of the Angela Merkel bloc was four percentage points higher.
The personal rating of the German Chancellor, who heads the German government for the fourth consecutive term, is also decreasing.
Today, 48 percent of Germans are in support of Angela Merkel, which is 7 percent lower than last year.
Next to the Social Democrats are green (15%), left (11%) and liberals (10%).
Evolution of "Alternatives"
The "Alternative for Germany" party was established in September 2012 on the basis of the group "Alternative Choice 2013," which included immigrants from the Christian Democratic Union.
The group initially stood in opposition to the government course, but at first it dealt only with economic issues, including the problems of the euro and cooperation within the EU.
At the same time, the group opposed the "sponsoring" Germany of the weak economies of the EU, did not rule out the possibility of returning to the German mark and the complete withdrawal of the country from the European Union.
Against the backdrop of the deepening immigration crisis, the AfD's political platform has expanded.
In 2013, the group formed a full-fledged party that occupied a niche of Euroskeptics and began to harshly criticize the government for the failure of immigration policy.
In the last parliamentary elections in 2017, the AfD managed to make its way to the Bundestag for the first time, receiving 94 seats (out of 709).
Two representatives of the "Alternatives for Germany" will get seats in the European Parliament.
