Named the death of the universe
The universe will last about 140 billion years, ten times the age of the world, equal to about 13.8 billion years.
The study of the international team of scientists is published in the library of electronic preprints arXiv.org and is aimed at the publication in the journal Publications of the Astronomical Society of Japan, according to the Japanese newspaper Asahi Shimbun.
To such conclusions, experts came, observing with the help of the camera HSC (Hyper Suprime-Cam) telescope Subaru for about ten million galaxies.
Having tracked the distribution of dark matter and dark energy, which accounts for more than 95 percent of the energy-mass of the observed world, scientists working as part of the standard cosmological model CDM (Cold Dark Matter), evaluated the rate of expansion of the Universe, which was a little slower than previously thought.
In a press release, the Subaru Observatory notes that the observations allowed to obtain a detailed three-dimensional map of the distribution of matter in the Universe, and the records of the data of the European Space Telescope Planck clarified the restrictions imposed on the parameters of the CDM.
In July, scientists simulated the possible death of the universe.
