The United States is thinking about the naval blockade of Russia because of the supply of oil and gas
In the United States, a naval blockade of Russia can begin to gain an advantage in the global energy market.
The US authorities have so zealously engaged in the fight for success in the global hydrocarbon market that they are ready to resort to a naval blockade of Russia, which remains one of the world's main suppliers of energy.
About the possibility of a naval blockade the day before was told by the head of the US Interior Ministry Ryan Zinke.
Contrary to world practice, the U.S. Department of the Interior performs civil functions, including natural resource policies.
Therefore, Zinke's statement was quite within the competence of the department headed by him, although it was not deprived of political color.
Speaking at an industrial event in Pittsburgh, Zinck said that thanks to the US Navy, the US Navy controls the sea routes in the Middle East and could block them if necessary.
From the words of Zinke it follows that the need may be associated with Washington's desire to interfere with Russian supplies to the global energy market.
Zinke reminded that Russia still receives the lion's share of its revenues from supplies to the world oil and gas market.
The desire to distribute energy supplies in the Middle East as well as in Eastern Europe was the main motive for Moscow's revitalization in the region, Zinke said.
The minister made it clear that the United States continues to hope to ensure leadership in the global energy market, becoming the largest supplier of oil and gas.
To do this, Washington will have to oust Russia both Iran and the naval blockade of trade routes - an acceptable measure on this path, Zinke believes.
